===Etymology 1===
From [[w:Walter Henry Medhurst|Medhurst]]<ref>{{cite-book|author=W[alter] H[enry] Medhurst|authorlink=Walter Henry Medhurst|title=An English and Japanese, and Japanese and English Vocabulary: Compiled from Native Works|location=Batavia|publisher=[s.n.]|year=1830|oclc=758334277}}.</ref> and [[w:James Curtis Hepburn|Hepburn]]’s<ref>{{cite-book|author=J[ames] C[urtis] Hepburn|authorlink=James Curtis Hepburn|title=A Japanese and English Dictionary: With an English and Japanese Index|location=Shanghai|publisher=[[w:Presbyterian World Mission|American Presbyterian Mission Press]]|year=1867|oclc=695232154}}.</ref> romanizations, under the influence of earlier {{der|en|pt|-}} romanizations, of {{der|en|ja|圓||[[round#Adjective|round]]; a [[round#Adjective|round]] [[object]]}} as ''ye'' or ''yen'', now {{m|ja|円|tr=en}}, from {{der|en|zh|銀圓|tr=yínyuán||round [[silver#Adjective|silver]] object(s), ''especially'' a [[piece of eight]]}}: {{m|zh|銀||silver}} + {{m|zh|圓||[[circular]], round; [[yuan]], yen, [[dollar]]}}.<ref>{{cite-book|entry=Yen|title={{lang|ja|世界大百科事典}}|trans-title=Sekai dai Hyakka Jiten = [[w:Heibonsha World Encyclopedia|Heibonsha World Encyclopedia]]|location=Tokyo|publisher=Heibonsha|year=2007|volume=III|oclc=693636727}}.</ref> Cognate with {{cog|zh|元|tr=yuán||[[monetary unit]], ''especially'' [[RMB]]}} and {{cog|ko|원||[[North Korea|North]] or [[South Korea]]n [[won]]}}. {{doublet|en|won|yuan}}.
====Noun====
{{en-noun|yen}}
# The [[monetary unit|unit]] of Japanese [[currency]] (symbol: [[¥]]) since 1871, [[divide]]d into 100 [[sen]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=The Export of Rice|newspaper=The Japan Weekly Mail: A Political, Commercial, and Literary Journal|location=Yokohama|publisher={{lang|ja|ジャパンメール新聞社}} = Japan Meru Shinbunsha|date=24 February 1872|volume=III|issue=8|page=95, column 1|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBJDAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA95|oclc=931924335|passage=Passing by those clauses of it which demand no notice, we arrive at that which provides that "each proposal (for purchase) must state the price per picul of rice in gold '''''yen'''''." But why in gold '''''yen''''', a coin as yet so scarce as to be almost beyond the ken of the foreign merchant?}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=G[opal] K[rishna] Gokhale|authorlink=Gopal Krishna Gokhale|chapter=Budget Speech, 1906|title=Speeches of the Honourable Mr. G. K. Gokhale, C.I.E.|location=Madras|publisher=Published by [[w:G. A. Natesan|G[anapathi] A[graharam] Natesan & Co.]], Esplanade|date=28 March 1906|year_published=[1908]|pages=171–172|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=oDYQAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA172|oclc=19902031|passage=Does any one however believe that Japan's glorious achievements would have been possible, if the Government of that country had merely poured money like water on its standing battalions, unaugmented by reserves, and the magnificent spirit of every man, woman and child in that country had not been behind the Army to support it? Japan's ordinary budget for the Army is only about 37.3 millions '''yen''', or a little under six crores of rupees.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Rei Kimura|chapter=7|title=Japanese Orchid|location=[Bangkok?]|publisher=Bangkok Books|year=2011|page=38|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LUvGc-dIkmUC&pg=PA38|isbn=978-616-245-048-8|passage=Taking the cue from his neighbours, Paul fed three 1000 '''yen''' notes into a machine beside the TV screen and the silent screen immediately exploded into a kaleidoscope of colours and instructions in Japanese below at least twenty pictures of sexy girls. {{...}} Paul hesitated staring intently at the screen and the waiting girl while the 3,000 '''yen''' he had fed into the machine steadily dwindled at the rate of 50 '''yen''' a minute.}}
# A [[coin]] or [[banknote|note]] worth [[one]] yen.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Richard Werner|authorlink=Richard Werner|chapter=Preface|title=Princes of the Yen: Japan’s Central Bankers and the Transformation of the Economy|location=Armonk, N.Y.|publisher={{w|M. E. Sharpe}}|year=2003|isbn=978-0-7656-1048-5|passage=When banks lend, they create money out of nothing, without withdrawing it from other parts of the economy. This way, fiscal policy would not have crowded out private-sector activity '''yen''' by '''yen''', as actually happened.}}
