#*: She repeated the words: "You for me and me for you," then hummed: "Two for tea and tea for two&nbsp;…" Her voice trailed off&nbsp;… "All I got is a '''yen''' for Diana and my sweet little cute little Zigzag."
#* {{quote-journal|en|url=https://classic.esquire.com/article/1936/2/1/the-crack-up|title=The Crack-Up|month=February|year=1936|author=F. Scott Fitzgerald|authorlink=F. Scott Fitzgerald|work=Esquire|passage=Like most middle-westerners, I have never had any but the vaguest race prejudices—I always had a secret '''yen''' for the lovely Scandinavian blondes who sat on porches in St. Paul but hadn’t emerged enough economically to be part of what was then society.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Natalie Angier|authorlink=Natalie Angier|chapter=Of Hoggamus and Hogwash: Putting Evolutionary Psychology on the Couch|title=Woman: An Intimate Biography|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|Houghton Mifflin Company]]|year=1999|page=382|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=NIonAf-m9OwC&pg=PT382|isbn=978-0-395-69130-4|passage=If a fellow chooses to tell himself that his '''yen''' for the fetching young intern in his office and his concomitant disgruntlement with his aging wife's housekeeping lacunae make perfect Darwinian sense, who am I to argue with him?}}
